Title: Hunger: A Memoir of (My) Body
Author: Roxane Gay
My Review: Roxane Gay explores the many paradoxes of her life in this memoir. The most common of these is her simultaneous desire to not be seen, but at the same time, to be seen. She is also spends a lot of time discussing her struggle to reconcile her parents' image of her as a "good" girl with who she was forced to become as a result of being raped at 12. I am also glad that she acknowledged how privileged she was compared to others: attending one of the best high schools in the country, having parents who were always there despite not knowing until recently the reasons behind her extreme behavior, to name just two. One of my favorite quotes from the book (transcribed from the audio version) was: "We talked about the goings on of the world, we talked about we wanted for ourselves. I took it for granted that this is what all families did. Come together and become an island unto themselves, the kitchen table the sun around which we revolved". (Chapter 14)

Title: Everything I Never Told You
Author: Celeste Ng
My Review: This is a book about the complexity of family dynamics.   It shows the power each member's expectations and anxieties can have on other members of the family unit, whether intentional or unintentional. I enjoyed viewing the story from each character's perspective and could empathize with all of them. I look forward to reading more by Celeste Ng.

Title: Beartown (Beartown, #1)
Author: Fredrik Backman
My Review: It is hard to write a review for this book. It is difficult to say I enjoyed a book on such a serious topic, especially since I wasn't expecting it when I began reading. However, what I can say is that Backman is an amazing writer. There is a large cast of characters, all of whom are written with such detail that you feel like you know them personally. Although this book focuses entirely on Beartown, a small town in Sweden (?), it could be any town in any part of America.  It raises important questions about what it means to be a part of a community, in this case, a community that revolves around hockey.

Title: The Last Mrs. Parrish
Author: Liv Constantine
My Review: This book kept me hooked from start to finish.  As a Fairfield county resident, the setting of Bishops Harbor, it was fascinating to get an inside view into the extremely rich (albeit it fictional). The chapters narrated by Daphne in Part 2 especially kept me on the edge of my seat. Although I was able to predict some of the twists in advance, there were enough surprises that I thoroughly enjoyed listening to this book. I really appreciated how the plot jumped several months at several different places which sped up the story, especially given that the book was already pretty long.

Title: The Power of Myth
Author: Joseph Campbell
My Review: I read this book in high school and it had a profound effect on me.  I even have a quote hanging in my room by Joseph Campbell about following your bliss. I hadn't quite realized how many of his ideas had seeped into my way of thinking until listening to it recently, some 14 years later. This time around, I finished the book with more questions than answers and many areas where I felt like I didn't quite get Campbell's point, which I believe is his goal. Because of this, I look forward to revisiting this again at some point in the future.

Title: Meditations
Author: Marcus Aurelius
Additional Authors: Martin Hammond, Albert Wittstock, Diskin Clay

Title: Uprooted
Author: Naomi Novik
My Review: I have very mixed feelings about this book.  Novik did an amazing job of writing the Wood as the antagonist.  The fear and creepiness of the Wood was very believable. There were also lots of questions that were left open regarding Agnieszka's magical capabilities and more generally about the magical world they lived in.  A desire to understand both the magic and the Wood made me want to keep reading.  On the other hand, after finishing the book, I still had lots of unanswered questions about both which frustrated me.  I also though the book dragged at some points and was a bit too long.  <spoiler> Lastly, the romantic relationship between Agnieszka and the Dragon wasn't well developed.  Either it should have been removed altogether or better integrated throughout the novel. </spoiler>

Title: Brave New World
Author: Aldous Huxley
My Review: I first read this book in high school and have since listed it as one of my favorites. This book introduced me to my favorite genre: dystopian fiction. After re-reading it recently, I'm not sure I'd still list it as a favorite; there are many others I preferred such as [b:Oryx and Crake|46756|Oryx and Crake (MaddAddam, #1)|Margaret Atwood|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1494109986s/46756.jpg|3143431] and [b:Station Eleven|20170404|Station Eleven|Emily St. John Mandel|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1451446835s/20170404.jpg|28098716].  I still enjoyed this re-read and will always be grateful that it exposed me to this type of literature.

Title: Big Magic: Creative Living Beyond Fear
Author: Elizabeth Gilbert
My Review: I really enjoyed this book, although I must say, I didn't buy into ALL of Elizabeth Gilbert's magical thinking. Some of the take away points for me were: 1) Being creative is inherent to being human; human beings were creating long before even agriculture/farming began. Creating is an important part of living a fulfilled life. 2) You should focus on the process, not necessarily the product. It doesn't matter how good you are if it brings you joy (to drag [a:Marie Kondō|5589647|Marie Kondō|https://images.gr-assets.com/authors/1451520607p2/5589647.jpg] into this). 3) Done is better than good.  As a perfectionist, this one really struck home for me! 4) You shouldn't rely on your creative endeavors to support you financially.  This very rarely happens and can end up destroying your urge to create. 5) Follow your curiosity; not all great ideas are "inspired" but rather come from continuous movement forward. She gives an example about how her interest in gardening led many years later to [b:The Signature of All Things|17465453|The Signature of All Things|Elizabeth Gilbert|https://images.gr-assets.com/books/1505847511s/17465453.jpg|21889418]. 6) She talks about the idea of movement vs. inertia. When facing a creative roadblock, its better to keep moving forward, even if on something totally unrelated rather than doing nothing until your creativity comes back.

Title: Mrs. Fletcher
Author: Tom Perrotta
My Review: This was one weird book; not at all what I was expecting.  It seemed like the author was trying to check every box related to sexuality: gay, straight, bi, trans, asexual, etc. The book also touches on sexual assault and pornography.  It just seemed like too many topics to do any of them appropriate justice.  Given all of this, the ending surprised me.  <spoiler> Eve's marriage to an "appropriately" aged man made me wonder what kind of message the author was sending - was a "normal" relationship required in order to be happily ever after? </spoiler>  2.5 stars, would not recommend to a friend.

Title: Unexpectedly Hers (Sterling Canyon, #3)
Author: Jamie Beck
My Review: 3.5 stars - After really enjoying Sterling Canyon book #2 (Trip and Kelsey), I knew my expectations were probably set too high for this book.  I didn't quite feel as connected to Emma and Wyatt.  Because of this, I wasn't as invested in their relationship or in a rush to finish the book. That being said, it was still a great read for a casual, lazy weekend and I don't regret reading it.

Title: What Happened
Author: Hillary Rodham Clinton
My Review: I had mixed feelings going into this, but overall I think HRC had several interesting points to make and I enjoyed the listen.  The first point she made was regarding the media coverage of DJT, which even though mostly negative, far exceeded coverage of her.  This is an example of "any publicity is good publicity." The other interesting point is that the media spent 3 times as much time covering her email scandal than any of her policies combined.  The most interesting point came at the end of the book when she discusses how Americans are now less involved in churches, community organizations, teams, etc.  Because of this, they no longer feel like they are a part of something bigger and are dissatisfied with their circumstances, leaving room for people like DJT to fill the gap. I've heard about this phenomenon before (most recently in Johnathan Haidt's The Righteous Mind).  Figuring out how to reconnect people with each other is probably one of the most important tasks we face going forward as a society.  Social media/cell phones/technology is not the answer.  Lastly, HRC spent considerable time talking about her relationships with her mother, daughter, and grandchildren. Because of this, I felt much more connected to her while reading this book than I ever did while she was a candidate. Where was this side of her on the campaign trail? Maybe it was there but overshadowed by all of the email and DJT coverage?

Title: The Hundred Lies of Lizzie Lovett
Author: Chelsea Sedoti
My Review: I have really mixed feelings about this book.  Based on the description, I expected this book to be a detective type story, which it mostly definitely was not.  This is really a coming of age story for Hawthorn, a high school senior, sparked by the death of Lizzie Lovett, a girl a few years older who seemed to have the perfect life.  I found Hawthorn to be quite immature and bizarre for her age and didn't find some of her actions very realistic<spoiler> (like hanging out with Lizzie's much older bf who was the last person with her before she disappeared)</spoiler>.  I kept going, and slowly but surely, the book (and Thorny) grew on me. In the end, I neither loved or hated the book; it was just fine.  Hawthorn does grow throughout the book and ultimately comes to some important realizations about life by the end.

Title: Why Not Me?
Author: Mindy Kaling
Publisher: Penguin Random House Audio Publishing Group
My Review: (3.5 stars) I haven't read Mindy Kaling's first book, so I'm not sure how much overlap there is between the two. Given that, I really enjoyed the majority of this book.  I appreciated her perspective as a successful actress/writer in Hollywood who doesn't look like everyone else.  As a huge fan of The Office, I appreciated the insider stories she shared from the show.  Her honesty in the chapter on her relationship with BJ Novak was particularly moving.  As for negatives, I found a few parts to be unnecessary, including the descriptions of current TV pilots and the email exchange in her fictitious life as a HS Latin teacher.  Listening to this book knowing that she is now pregnant (with no mention of the father of the baby) makes me hopeful that she will write another book on this new chapter of her life.

Title: Secretly Hers (Sterling Canyon, #2)
Author: Jamie Beck
My Review: This is the 3rd Jamie Beck book that I have read so far. Thanks to Trip, this has been my favorite!  I enjoyed this book much more than Accidentally Hers, probably because Trip and Kelsey's story wasn't as dramatic as Avery and Grey's.  The nature of their agreement also made this book steamy almost from the beginning. As a 31 year old looking for my own prince charming, I could very much identify with Kelsey's longing for a husband and a family. I am also glad that both characters stayed true to themselves, making their HEA more believable. On to book 3 in the series...

Title: Snow Flower and the Secret Fan
Author: Lisa See
My Review: This is the story of a friendship between two Chinese girls over the course of their lifetimes.  The love the two girls share for each other is stronger than the love they have for their parents, husbands, and even their children.  The relationship was multi-faceted and felt very authentic; the author did a great job of capturing its complexity.  I especially found the details on life as a woman in China during this time period fascinating (and heart-wrenching).
